0\">Objects are globally referenceable.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1351\" data-end=\"1372\">\n<p data-start=\"1353\" data-end=\"1372\">Identity is stable.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1373\" data-end=\"1403\">\n<p data-start=\"1375\" data-end=\"1403\">Sharing is capability-based.</p>\n</li>\n<li data-start=\"1404\" data-end=\"1461\">\n<p data-start=\"1406\" data-end=\"1461\">The storage backend becomes replaceable infrastructure.</p>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p data-start=\"1463\" data-end=\"1647\">In effect, you are describing a programmable personal data layer with portable authority. It solves backup, cross-device sync, and sharing — but without requiring surrender of control.</p>\n<p data-start=\"1649\" data-end=\"1922\">The real constraint isn’t technical; it’s ecosystem coordination. The primitives (CRDTs, content addressing, capability tokens, log replication) already exist. What’s missing is a widely adopted, backend-agnostic standard that combines them into a coherent developer model.</p>\n<p data-start=\"1924\" data-end=\"2010\" data-is-last-node=\"\" data-is-only-node=\"\">That is the structural difference between “cloud app” and “user-sovereign data layer.”</p></div></div></div></div><div class=\"z-0 flex min-h-[46px] justify-start\"></div><div class=\"mt-3 w-full empty:hidden\"><div class=\"text-center\"></div></div></div></div></article></div><div aria-hidden=\"true\" data-edge=\"true\" class=\"pointer-events-none h-px w-px absolute bottom-0\"></div>",
